    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Ockham Monday. 7 o'clock</p>
      <p>Dearest. You will like to hear that I am doing very well. It is fortunate however that I did not attempt going to Fryern today. Dr Kay found it necessary to give me more laudanum &amp;c before luncheon today; &amp; it was not possible for me</p>
      <p>to think of going out even. But I have had a capital sleep this afternoon, &amp; am much refreshed now, &amp; mending fast. Dr Kay left, with the [brats? boats?], about three.--</p>
      <p>He most kind, &amp; leaving us all more than ever attached to him, particularly myself.--</p>
      <p>Indeed I will try &amp; attend to everything he says to me; &amp; I never</p>
      <p>can sufficiently be grateful &amp; attached to him for all his kindness and friendship for me.--</p>
      <p>He has been also most attentive &amp; kind to Charlotte;-- who is fully sensible of it; &amp; whom he is to continue to attend in Town.--</p>
      <p>I have written to the Hen. I fear she will have sent me a letter to Fryern today.</p>
      <p>Dearest Mate; forgive the</p>
      <p>poor naughty sick Bird. May it be</p>
      <p>Avis Phoneix?--</p>
    </div></body>
